0.title: Rules
0.body:
[u][b]Carcassonne[/b][/u]

On the table there is the official game, along with the Rivers expansion and the Inns & Cathedrals expansion. If you're just starting off, I suggest just using the official game for now and getting rid of the other tiles. The tiles you are using need to be placed in the drawing bag. Pick up the stack of cards by holding left click, then hold them above the bag. Use Alt + Right click to drop the bottom tile into the bag, repeat until all the tiles are seperated inside. The number on the bag after putting the entire official game tiles in should be 71.

71 + 18 = 89 (With Inns & Cathedrals Expansion)

Do not mix in the river expansion! I will explain how that works in the next part:

At the start of the game, each player takes 7 small meeples (the coloured people) of a single colour of their choosing and a large meeple if they are playing with the Inns & Cathedrals expansion and places them in front of their name. (Picking the ones which match the colour of your name would be the most helpful.) The starting tile is always used to begin the game unless you are using the river expansion. I suggest moving everything else out of the way that you're not using, or just deleting them.

For the river expansion, you begin with the river starting tile and put the ending card aside for now. You flip the rest of the cards upside down, shuffle them and draw one at a time on each player's turn until the deck runs out and the river automatically finishes with the river ending tile. You may place meeples on features as you place each tile as you would normally do. While placing, you must prioritise the river. The river cannot go round to form a U turn. The river cannot be claimed/does not contain any scoring.

When it gets to your turn, you draw a single tile from the drawing bag.

Place tiles so that everything lines up, you may rotate the tile. City bits should go next to city bits, field bits should go next to field bits and road bits should go next to other road bits. Cloisters may be placed anywhere in an open space that doesn't disrupt any other features being built. Tiles have to be placed perpendicular to a tile already on the board. They cannot be placed diagonally.

Once a tile is placed, you may place one of your meeples to claim a feature on that tile. For example, you could decide to claim the road that leads on to the card you drew.

You may not place a meeple on an already claimed feature, though if the tiles are seperated you may place one there and attempt to 'merge' the tiles with a connecting piece. This can become a bit of a war ground as the one with the most meeples on the feature wins all the points. If meeples of multiple colours all have the same amount of meeples on a single feature, you each get all the available points for that feature. Large meeples are worth two points instead of one, so a good strategy is to use those when planning to steal the points from another feature with only one meeple occupying.

To complete a feature, a city has to be surrounded by walls, a road has to have two intersections where the road appears to be parted, and a field has to be completely surrounded by any feature(s). Once a feature is completed, any meeples on the completed feature can be placed back in to your hand.

When scoring points, you move your extra coloured meeple round the scoring pad to the appropiate number. These meeples have to stay by/on the scoring pad and you cannot use them in the game. If you manage to go round the scoreboard to the end, flip your meeple so it faces down to signify you've been round the board once already and continue to score. You may agree on any meeple orientation on the game board if you continue to complete the game board a second time, it's not that important.

With/without the Inns&Cathedrals expansion, you may use the 50/100 point scoring tiles and hand them out to players who have passed round the board multiple times to keep track rather than the above rules found in the official game. Or you could write each passing in the notepad, whatever suits your play style.

During the game, the scoring are as follows:

• After completing a city, each city tile is worth 2 points each. Also, any shields found on the city are worth 2 points extra.
With a cathedral each city tile is worth 3 points instead of 2, the same goes for shields.

• After completing a road, each road tile is worth 1 point per tile.

• After completing a cloister with 8 tiles surrounding it, it is scored for 1 point + 1 point for all the surrounding tiles. (9 points total)

• Fields are not scored until the end of the game.

After the game, the scoring are as follows:

• All uncompleted features at the end of the game score 1 point per tile, including shields.

• If a city contains a cathedral from the Inns & Cathedrals expansion, or a road contains an inn from the same expansion (the little lake/house) and is uncompleted, the feature scores 0 points.

• Fields = 3 points for each completed city bordering the field.

The scores are counted up and the winner is the person with the most points on the scoreboard. (50 * number of times gone round) + number on board.
